			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?t=59390&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 21 Jul 2008 06:00:38 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>So, I went and upgraded my machine recently in order to support HD playback on my Windows Vista Ultimate Edition. For reference, my computer scores a 5.3 out of 5.9 by the Vista Experience Index, due to my processor being a lowly 4.5GHz (WTF?). Other than the processor, the rest of the specs on my...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>So, I went and upgraded my machine recently in order to support HD playback on my Windows Vista Ultimate Edition. For reference, my computer scores a 5.3 out of 5.9 by the Vista Experience Index, due to my processor being a lowly 4.5GHz (WTF?). Other than the processor, the rest of the specs on my system peg to 5.9 cap.<br />
<br />
Anyway, I got a Sony BD player from Best Buy for $150 and installed it on a free SATA channel. Drive came up and was recognized without any trouble, but unfortunately Windows Media Center does not decode BD. Thankfully, the drive comes with a limited version of PowerDVD and from what I've seen, you can also play BD with the latest version of WinDVD. Hopefully, Microsoft will get a BD decoder license for Media Player at some point, I don't like having two movie playing applications.<br />
<br />
I did find a hack of sorts that allows you to configure WMP so that it will launch PowerDVD or WinDVD whenever it finds a Blu-ray disc. That's better than nothing, I suppose. HD on the PC looks great!</div>

]]></content:encoded>
